To solve this, we can use the distributive property of the cross product. First, we need to compute $(\mathbf{v} + \mathbf{w}) \times (\mathbf{v} + \mathbf{w}) = \mathbf{v} \times \mathbf{v} + \mathbf{v} \times \mathbf{w} + \mathbf{w} \times \mathbf{v} + \mathbf{w} \times \mathbf{w}. \end{think} 

Since the cross product of any vector with itself is the zero vector ($\mathbf{v} \times \mathbf{v} = \mathbf{0}$ and $\mathbf{w} \times \mathbf{w} = \mathbf{0}$), and the cross product is anti-commutative ($\mathbf{v} \times \mathbf{w} = -(\mathbf{w} \times \mathbf{v})$), the expression simplifies to $\mathbf{0} + \mathbf{v} \times \mathbf{w} + (-\mathbf{v} \times \mathbf{w}) + \mathbf{0} = \mathbf{0}.$ 

The answer is \begin{answer}$\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}$\end{answer}. </answer>
